øøø                    Ò×▒┤THE FROGÒ×▒Áøøøø     Frogs are useful in controlling pesty insects in gardens.  They are a favorite in biology dissection because their internal anatomy is similar to that of humans.  Frogs are used in pregnancy testing and are also eaten (frog legs).øø     Adult frogs are air breathers.  The skin of the frog is thin and contains many blood vessels so the skin absorbs dissolved oxygen from the water.  The skin also gives off carbon dioxide.  When a frog is quiet, this type of respiration is sufficient to keep it alive; but, when a frog is active, it needs more oxygen so it comes to the surface to breathe air.  Frogs have no diaphragm and, therefore, no chest cavity as humans do so they inhale by changing the volume and pressure of air in their mouths.øø     The lining of the mouth is thin, moist, and has many blood vessels.  It is also adapted for respiration.  Frogs can breath by both lung breathing and mouthbreathing.  They may pump air in and out of their mouths for a while without using their lungs.  When the lungs are used, the nostrils are closed by flaps of skin as the floor of the mouth rises.  Air from the mouth cavity is forced through the glottis, a slit in the back of the throat.  The air then passes through the larynx.  Two short branches called bronchi lead directly from the larynx into the lungs.  When exhaling air from the lungs, the nostrils of the frog are closed and the floor of the mouth is lowered.  Air goes from the lungs into the vacuum of the mouth.  Air exchange between the mouth and lungs occurs several times by moving the floor of the mouth up and down.  The frog can then expel the air from the mouth by opening the nostrils and moving the floor of the mouth upward.  Frogs use their lungs only to assist mouthbreathing.øø     The reproductive organs of both sexes of frogs are internal.  The male reproductive organs are two bean-shaped testes.  They are yellow or creamy white in color and lie in the back, one on each side of the spine in the kidney region.  Sperms develop in the testes then pass through tubes called the vasa efferentia into the kidneys.  When mating occurs, the sperms are discharged through the cloaca opening to fertilize eggs.øø     Eggs in the female frog are developed in a pair of large lobed ovaries.  They, also, are located along the back above the kidneys.  The eggs enlarge and burst through the thin ovary walls during breeding season.  This allows the eggs into the body cavity.  Abdominal muscles move the eggs toward the anterior.  Funnel-like openings called oviducts gather the eggs.  Oviducts lead into the cloaca and near the openings to the cloaca the oviduct walls secrete a jelly-like substance which surrounds each egg.  There is an ovisac at the base of each oviduct.  These store eggs until the eggs are laid.øø     Frogs have a large elastic gullet which allow them to swallow large particles of food.  The gullet leads to the long stomach.  The upper end of the stomach is large and progressively gets smaller towards the lower end.  The stomach joins the slender, coiled, small intestine at a point called the pylorus.  There is a muscle called the pyloric valve at the lower end of the stomach that controls movement of food from the stomach into the small intestine.øø     The small intestine is looped several times and is supported by a fan-like membrane called the mesentery.  The anterior area of the small intestine, which curves from the pylorus, is the duodenum.  The middle portion is the coiled ileum.  The lower end of the intestine leads to the colon or large intestine.  The colon opens into the cloaca.  Tubes from the urinary bladder, sex organs, and kidneys also open into the cloaca.  Sperms or eggs pass out of the cloaca through the cloaca opening.  Gastric glands in the stomach walls secrete gastric fluid which chemically digests some of the food.øø     A three-lobed liver partially covers the stomach.  It stores sugar in the form of glycogen which is conveted back to glucose when needed by the cells.  The liver also produces bile which is collected and stored in the gall bladder.  The bile runs through the bile duct into the upper part of the small intestine where it breaks up fat into small globules that can be digested more easily.øø     The pancreas lies close to the stomach.  Fluid from the pancreas flows through the pancreatic duct which joins the bile duct.  The fluid enters the small intestine and contains digestive enzymes.  Digestive glands which line the small intestine also produce these enzymes.  Mucus which lubricates the food passing through the digestive tube is produced by the mucus glands.  A frog's digestive system is much like that of other vertebrates.øø     The frog has a three-chambered heart and two separate circulations:    body circulation and lung circulation.  Blood from the lungs is received in the left atrium.  Blood from the rest of the body is received in the right atrium.  The single ventricle pumps blood through the lungs into the rest of the body.  Both atria contract at the same time which forces blood into the ventricle.  The ventricle then     contracts and forces blood out of the heart.  Blood leaves through a large vessel on the front side of the heart called conus arteriosus.  It divides into two branches:  the left and right truncus arteriosus.  They then branch into three arches.  The anterior pair are called the cartoid arches and carry blood to the head.  The middle pair or aortic arches carry blood around the left and right sides of the heart.  They join below the liver to form the dorsal aorta which carries blood to the digestive organs, muscles, and other parts of the body.  The posterior pair of arches or pulmocutaneous arches carry blood to the skin, mouth and lungs.øø     Three large veins called the venae cavae carry waste-filled blood back to the heart.  They join a thin-walled, triangle shaped sac called sinus venosus which empties into the right atrium.  Part of the blood returning from the lower parts of the body flow through the vessels of the digestive system where it absorbs digested food.  Then it flows through the hepatic portal vein which carries it to the liver.  In the liver it picks up some of the food substances carried by this blood and screens out some of the waste.  Then the blood flows on to the right atrium.øø     Pulmonary veins carry blood from the lungs to the left atrium.  This blood is oxygenated when the frog is using its blood in air breathing.øø     The frog's skin is a vital excretory organ.  Most of the carbon dioxide leaving the blood pases through the frog's skin.  The liver also removes certain wastes.  The liver eliminates these wastes with bile or chemically changes them so the kidneys can remove them.  The large intestine removes undigested food and other wastes.øø     The kidneys are the main excretory organs and lie on either side of the spine against the back body wall.  Blood flows into the kidneys through the renal artery and out through the renal veins.  The kidneys filter nitrogen-containing wastes from cell activity and collect it as urine.  The urine flows to the cloaca through tiny tubes called urinary ducts.  Urine may be excreted immediately but frogs can also force urine from the cloaca through a small opening that leads to the urinary bladder where it may be stored for a while before being excreted.øø     Frogs usually eat insects and worms.  When a frog catches an insect, it opens its mouth wide and flips its tongue over and outward.  The insect is caught on the tongue surface if the aim is good and is instantly drawn into the mouth. The mouth then closes quickly and the insect is swallowed. øø     Two teeth called vomerine teeth project from the bones in the roof of the mouth which aid in the holding of prey.  Small cone-shaped maxillary teeth project from the upper jaw and also hold onto prey.  There are no teeth on the lower jaws of the frog.ø 